{"parse":{"title":"Hastividyarnava","pageid":9480352,"revid":860066995,"text":{"*":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><div class=\"thumb tright\"><div class=\"thumbinner\" style=\"width:222px;\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Art_hastividyarnava_2.jpg\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/4/48/Art_hastividyarnava_2.jpg/220px-Art_hastividyarnava_2.jpg\" width=\"220\" height=\"132\" class=\"thumbimage\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/4/48/Art_hastividyarnava_2.jpg/330px-Art_hastividyarnava_2.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/4/48/Art_hastividyarnava_2.jpg/440px-Art_hastividyarnava_2.jpg 2x\" data-file-width=\"500\" data-file-height=\"300\" /></a>  <div class=\"thumbcaption\"><div class=\"magnify\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Art_hastividyarnava_2.jpg\" class=\"internal\" title=\"Enlarge\"></a></div>A folio from the <b>Hastividyarnava</b> manuscript</div></div></div>\n<p>The <b>Hastividy\u0101rnava</b>, written by Sukumar Barkaith, is one of the best known illustrated manuscripts of <a href=\"/wiki/Assam\" title=\"Assam\">Assam</a>.  Commissioned under the patronage of King <a href=\"/wiki/Siva_Singha\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Siva Singha\">Siva Singha</a> (1713-1744 C.E.) and his queen consort <a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Phuleswari&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1\" class=\"new\" title=\"Phuleswari (page does not exist)\">Phuleswari</a>, it deals with the management and care of <a href=\"/wiki/Indian_elephant\" title=\"Indian elephant\">elephants</a> in the royal stables.<sup id=\"cite_ref-Barkaith_1-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Barkaith-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>The Hastividy\u0101rnava is a work that arose in a matrix of disciplined study, prolonged observation and a precedent tradition. The commission of such a treatise was perhaps considered important as the elephant played an important role in affirming the idea of monarchy and exercising state power.<sup id=\"cite_ref-Barua_2-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Barua-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<div id=\"toc\" class=\"toc\"><input type=\"checkbox\" role=\"button\" id=\"toctogglecheckbox\" class=\"toctogglecheckbox\" style=\"display:none\" /><div class=\"toctitle\" lang=\"en\" dir=\"ltr\"><h2>Contents</h2><span class=\"toctogglespan\"><label class=\"toctogglelabel\" for=\"toctogglecheckbox\"></label></span></div>\n<ul>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-1\"><a href=\"#Contents\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">1</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Contents</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-2\"><a href=\"#Artists\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">2</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Artists</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-3\"><a href=\"#Current_location_and_status\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">3</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Current location and status</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-4\"><a href=\"#References\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">4</span> <span class=\"toctext\">References</span></a></li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Contents\">Contents</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Hastividyarnava&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: Contents\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>The treatise itself was written for a ruling monarch, and almost entirely from the view of sustaining <a href=\"/wiki/Monarchy\" title=\"Monarchy\">monarchy</a> \u2013 which elephants are suitable for the kingdom, how they should be trained for use by the nobility and for the purpose of war. The <i>Hastividy\u0101rnava</i> has an elaborate taxonomic system describing the various types of elephants and their character, and it was perhaps considered important for a king to have knowledge regarding elephants, as it is mentioned that only the learned king recognizes particular <a href=\"/wiki/Breed\" title=\"Breed\">breeds</a>.\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Artists\">Artists</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Hastividyarnava&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2\" title=\"Edit section: Artists\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>The two artists <i>Dilbar</i> and <i>Dosai</i> who painted the manuscript were probably not very familiar with the landscape of Assam and hence the quality of the landscapes are not of a very high standard.\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Current_location_and_status\">Current location and status</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Hastividyarnava&amp;action=edit&amp;section=3\" title=\"Edit section: Current location and status\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>The manuscript is currently housed in the Department of Historical and Antiquarian Studies (DHAS) in Guwahati, Assam.  The <i>Hastividyarnava</i> should not be confused with the <i>Hati-Puthi</i> of <i>Auniati Sattra</i> (Majuli), which is a much later work (possibly of the early 19th century).<sup id=\"cite_ref-3\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-3\">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"References\">References</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Hastividyarnava&amp;action=edit&amp;section=4\" title=\"Edit section: References\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"reflist\" style=\"list-style-type: decimal;\">\n<div class=\"mw-references-wrap\"><ol class=\"references\">\n<li id=\"cite_note-Barkaith-1\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-Barkaith_1-0\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">Barkaith, S. (1734). <i>Hastividyarnava.</i>  Edited with an introduction by P.C. Choudhury.  Guwahati: Publication Board, Assam.</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-Barua-2\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-Barua_2-0\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">Barua, M. (2005). The Elephant in Assamese History and Mythology. Kaziranga National Park Centenary Celebration Volume P. 34-39. Forest Department of Assam, Govt. of Assam.</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-3\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-3\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://www.srimanta.net/manuscript%20painting2.htm\">srimanta.org</a><sup class=\"noprint Inline-Template\"><span style=\"white-space: nowrap;\">&#91;<i><a href=\"/wiki/Wikipedia:Link_rot\" title=\"Wikipedia:Link rot\"><span title=\"&#160;Dead link since September 2018\">permanent dead link</span></a></i>&#93;</span></sup></span>\n</li>\n</ol></div></div>\n<p><br />\n</p>\n<table class=\"metadata plainlinks stub\" role=\"presentation\" style=\"background:transparent\"><tbody><tr><td><a href=\"/wiki/File:Flag_of_India.svg\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"Stub icon\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/4/41/Flag_of_India.svg/25px-Flag_of_India.svg.png\" width=\"25\" height=\"17\" class=\"thumbborder\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/4/41/Flag_of_India.svg/38px-Flag_of_India.svg.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/4/41/Flag_of_India.svg/50px-Flag_of_India.svg.png 2x\" data-file-width=\"1350\" data-file-height=\"900\" /></a></td><td><i>This article about the culture of India is a <a href=\"/wiki/Wikipedia:Stub\" title=\"Wikipedia:Stub\">stub</a>. You can help Wikipedia by <a class=\"external text\" href=\"//en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Hastividyarnava&amp;action=edit\">expanding it</a>.</i><div class=\"plainlinks hlist navbar mini\" style=\"position: absolute; right: 15px; display: none;\"><ul><li class=\"nv-view\"><a href=\"/wiki/Template:India-cultur